  "prompt": "Why is big G used in the formula of force?",
  "response": "In the context of the law of universal gravitation, \"big G\" (often denoted as \\( G \\)) is known as the gravitational constant. It is a fundamental physical constant that appears in the formula for gravitational force between two masses. The formula is given by:\n\n\\[\nF = G \\frac{m_1 m_2}{r^2}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( F \\) is the gravitational force between the two masses,\n- \\( m_1 \\) and \\( m_2 \\) are the two masses,\n- \\( r \\) is the distance between the centers of the two masses,\n- \\( G \\) is the gravitational constant.\n\nThe reason \"big G\" is used in this formula is to quantify the strength of the gravitational force in a way that can be consistently used across different scenarios. The value of \\( G \\) makes the units in the formula work out correctly, allowing for accurate calculations of gravitational force. \n\nThe gravitational constant \\( G \\) has a value of approximately \\( 6.674 \\times 10^{-11} \\, \\text{N m}^2/\\text{kg}^2 \\). Its inclusion in the formula allows for the correct scaling of the gravitational force based on the masses involved and the distance between them.\n\nThe designation \"big G\" helps distinguish this gravitational constant from other similar constants that may be involved in different contexts of physics, such as \"little g,\" which refers to the acceleration due to gravity at the surface of a planet.",
